1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,420
When we think about alien civilizations
知的生命体の文明について考えるとき

2
00:00:03,420 --> 00:00:08,400
we tend to look into the vastness of space, to far away planets.
広大な宇宙や遠い惑星に
目を向けがちだ

3
00:00:08,400 --> 00:00:15,010
But there is another incredibly vast dimension that we might be giving too little thought to:
だが、驚くほど広大なもう一つの次元には
ほとんど考えが及んでいない

4
00:00:15,010 --> 00:00:16,560
time
時間だ

5
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:23,740
Could it be that over the last hundreds of millions of years, other civilizations existed on earth?  
過去数億年にわたり
地球に別の文明が存在していたのでは？

6
00:00:23,740 --> 00:00:28,080
Indigenous technological species that rose and died out? 
土着の、技術を持つ種が台頭し
そして滅んだのでは？

7
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:32,630
And that they or their artifacts are buried beneath our feet? 
その種と、それらの遺物が
私たちの足元に埋まっているのでは？

8
00:00:32,630 --> 00:00:38,300
What does science have to say about this and what are the implications for us?
この疑問に科学はどう答えるだろう？
そして、私たちに何を示唆するだろう？

9
00:00:46,260 --> 00:00:49,810
Life on earth has existed for 4 billion years, 
地球上の生命は
40億年前から存在し

10
00:00:49,810 --> 00:00:54,840
mostly as single celled organisms until some 540 million years ago
5.4億年前までは
ほぼ単細胞生物だった

11
00:00:54,840 --> 00:00:58,620
the Cambrian explosion heralded the age of animals. 
カンブリア爆発で動物の時代になるまでは

12
00:00:58,620 --> 00:01:01,920
A huge time window for our indigenous aliens. 
土着の知的生命体にとって
巨大な猶予が存在する

13
00:01:01,920 --> 00:01:06,170
Where would we look for them and what could we hope to find?  
どこを探せば見つかるか
そして何を見ることになるのか？

14
00:01:06,170 --> 00:01:09,360
Sadly we have only one civilization to look at:
残念ながら、参照できる文明はたった一つで

15
00:01:09,360 --> 00:01:10,840
Ourselves.
人類自身のものだ

16
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:14,660
Anatomically modern humans emerged around 300,000 years ago
解剖学的にみて現生人類の出現は
約30万年前で

17
00:01:14,660 --> 00:01:19,940
and probably lived in small groups of hunter gatherers, slowly spreading around the world.
おそらく狩猟採集の小集団で生活し
緩やかに世界に広がっていった

18
00:01:19,940 --> 00:01:26,800
 Progress was slow and our lifestyle did not change much, although there may have been local bursts of complexity.
進歩は遅く、生活様式の変化も乏しかったが
局所的な高度化はあったかも

19
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:33,110
Until about 10,000 years ago, when the agricultural revolution changed our lifestyle forever, 
約1万年前、農業革命が
私たちの生活様式を一変させ

20
00:01:33,110 --> 00:01:37,270
enabling massive population growth and technological progress. 
大規模な人口増加と
技術的進歩が可能となった

21
00:01:37,270 --> 00:01:43,470
Rather than just animals with culture and tools that would have been invisible from space,  we changed the face of the planet, 
単なる「文化や道具をもった動物」でなく
宇宙から見た地球の外見まで変えてみせた

22
00:01:43,470 --> 00:01:50,670
cleared forests and constructed cities and temples for our gods at breathtaking speeds and scales.
驚異的な速さとスケールで
森林を切り拓き、都市と神殿をつくりあげたのだ

23
00:01:50,670 --> 00:01:55,200
Until about 300 years ago, we became an industrial species 
300年ほど前
私たちは工業を営む種となった

24
00:01:55,200 --> 00:02:01,000
Until about 300 years ago, we became an industrial species
またもや人口が飛躍的に増加し
地球への影響も大きくなった

25
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,840
We could say that our 300,000 year long history has three phases: 
人類30万年の歴史は
3段階に分けられるだろう

26
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:10,320
 We were hunter gatherers for 97%, farmers for 2.9%
97％は狩猟採集民として
2.9％は農耕民として

27
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:14,840
 and industrialists for 0.1% of our history.
そして0.1％が工業民だが

28
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:18,170
And yet we are super new on earth. 
そもそも人類自体が
地球では新顔だ

29
00:02:18,170 --> 00:02:23,800
On geological timescales, even the sturdiest things lose their durability. 
地質学的なタイムスケールでは
最も頑丈な物質さえ永続性を失う

30
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:29,880
The oldest large scale surface is in the Negev Desert, a meager 1.8 million years old. 
地表に最も長く存続しているのはネゲヴ砂漠で
180万年に過ぎない

31
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:36,930
 Everything older has been crushed to dust or turned over and it is either below the ground, or covered by ice or ocean.
より古いものは粉砕されたり分解されたりで
地下にあるか、氷や海に覆われている

32
00:02:36,930 --> 00:02:43,640
Our age, the Anthropocene will be a layer only a few centimeters thick in a few million years.
私たちの時代、人新世は数百万年後には
たった数cmの地層となるだろう

33
00:02:43,640 --> 00:02:49,660
If there were aliens before us and they too went through these three phases, what would remain of them? 
人類以前に知的生命体が存在し
この3段階を経たなら何が残るだろう

34
00:02:49,660 --> 00:02:56,320
What can we learn about indegnous aliens by looking at ourselves?
未知の知的生命体について
人類自身から何が示唆されるだろう

35
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:59,070
Hunter & Gatherer Aliens
狩猟採集型の知的生命体

36
00:02:59,070 --> 00:03:03,620
We actually know that in the last few million years, there were hunter gatherers aliens.  
ここ数百万年の間に
狩猟採集型の知的生命体は実在した

37
00:03:03,620 --> 00:03:08,530
Our ancestors like Homo Erectus and cousins like the Neanderthals or Denisovans
私たちの祖先、ホモ・エレクトスや
近縁のネアンデルタール人やデニソワ人

38
00:03:08,530 --> 00:03:13,440
and probably many more that we haven’t found yet or are lost to time forever. 
そして他にも未発見・発見不能の存在が
おそらく多数いたのだ

39
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:18,590
They left fragments of their bodies, of weapons and tools and even art. 
彼らは肉体の一部、武器や道具
あるいは芸術さえも残した

40
00:03:18,590 --> 00:03:24,380
Considering how long they existed and how little remains of them although they lived not that far from our present 
わりと近年まで、長く存続したのに
彼らの痕跡が少ないことを考慮すると 

41
00:03:24,380 --> 00:03:27,380
it is ​easy to think there have been others
他の存在も容易に想像できる

42
00:03:27,380 --> 00:03:34,000
Intelligent animals like us that could talk and use tools and fire, that had culture and art. 
私たちのような、言葉を話し、道具や火を扱い
文化や芸術を持つ知的な動物

43
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:38,180
For the last two million years, most hominins lived as hunter-gatherers – 
この200万年
ほとんどのヒト科は狩猟採集民だった

44
00:03:38,180 --> 00:03:41,380
 so if these aliens never moved up higher on the tech tree,
もし、次の技術段階に移行しないなら

45
00:03:41,380 --> 00:03:46,270
hundreds of different species and cultures could have existed without leaving any traces.
何百もの異なる種や文化が
痕跡を残さずに存在し得たのだ

46
00:03:46,270 --> 00:03:51,890
Their artifacts lost to biological and then geological processes.  
彼らの遺物は生物学的
そして地質学的プロセスにより失われたのだ

47
00:03:51,890 --> 00:03:57,270
At worst they would leave absolutely nothing to be found after thousands of years.
最悪の場合
数千年で痕跡が完全に消失する

48
00:03:57,270 --> 00:03:59,080
But what about fossils? 
だが化石は？

49
00:03:59,080 --> 00:04:04,540
 We talked about how unlikely the process of fossilization is in more detail in our dinosaur video, 
化石化の望みの薄さは
恐竜の動画で詳細に扱ったが

50
00:04:04,540 --> 00:04:11,530
 but in a nutshell, per hundred thousand years of earth's history we only get a handful of good fossils. 
ザックリいうと、良質な化石は
10万年で一握り程度しか得られないのだ

51
00:04:11,530 --> 00:04:14,770
 So we might easily just miss fossils of such people 
だから存在を見失い得るし

52
00:04:14,770 --> 00:04:20,770
– but even if we had any, we would not necessarily be able to identify them as hunter gatherers.
化石を見つけても
狩猟採集民と特定できるとは限らない

53
00:04:20,770 --> 00:04:24,090
Agricultural and Empire Aliens
農耕と帝国の知的生命体

54
00:04:24,090 --> 00:04:29,140
Looking at humans again, agricultural societies left much more to be dug up and found,  
人類に再び着目すると
農耕社会では発掘可能な痕跡が多く残される

55
00:04:29,140 --> 00:04:35,970
because they used more sophisticated tools made from sturdier materials and had to feed millions, leaving many more artifacts. 
彼らはより頑丈で洗練された道具を用い
何百万人も養ったため、多くの遺物を残したのだ

56
00:04:35,970 --> 00:04:43,520
Farming allowed them to specialize and develop tech from writing to navigation, architecture and government. 
農耕は専門分化を可能とし
文字、航海術、農耕、政治の技術を発展させた

57
00:04:43,520 --> 00:04:47,690
 Over thousands of years city states became kingdoms and empires,
何千年もかけ
都市国家は王国や帝国になり

58
00:04:47,690 --> 00:04:51,060
some existing for millennia before they fell.
滅びるまでに
数千年も存続したものもある

59
00:04:51,060 --> 00:04:55,200
Many of the buildings or monuments they constructed are still around
その建造物やモニュメントの多くは今も残り

60
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:59,300
and traces of them will exist for a few thousand more years.
その痕跡は数千年は存続するだろう

61
00:04:59,300 --> 00:05:05,490
Some only as outlines in the ground, but still recognizable to future archaeologists. 
一部は輪郭だけになるが
未来の考古学者にはわかるだろう

62
00:05:05,490 --> 00:05:12,340
The pyramids are piles of limestone so massive that they will probably be around for hundreds of thousands of years. 
ピラミッドは石灰岩の山であり
その巨大さから何十万年も存続しそうだ

63
00:05:12,340 --> 00:05:17,370
And because of the greater numbers of humans that lived during our farm and empire period,
また、より多くの人口が
農耕時代や帝国時代を生きたため

64
00:05:17,370 --> 00:05:23,700
we can expect way more fossils and artifacts to be detectable, maybe for a few million years before they vanish.
はるかに多くの化石や遺物が残るだろうし
消滅までに数百万年を要するかも

65
00:05:23,700 --> 00:05:30,710
So we can say with confidence that no such indigenous alien civilization existed in the last few million years 
だから、ここ数百万年では
土着の知的生命体による文明はなかったと断言できる

66
00:05:30,710 --> 00:05:34,340
because otherwise we would have found something that they left.
存在したなら
痕跡が当然みつかるからだ

67
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:38,060
This still leaves a window of hundreds of millions of years,
それでも、数億年の期間が候補として残る

68
00:05:38,060 --> 00:05:42,700
back to the emergence of complex life, where we would not be able to tell.
複雑な生命の誕生時点までさかのぼるなら
知りえないのだ

69
00:05:42,700 --> 00:05:48,600
 If there were alien pre industrial societies and empires on the level of the ancient Romans or Chinese,
もし古代のローマや中国レベルの前工業社会と帝国を
知的生命体が築いても

70
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:51,550
 they would have likely disappeared without a trace. 
跡形もなく消えているだろう

71
00:05:51,550 --> 00:05:55,530
Their tools, even advanced metals, would have rotted away
彼らの道具は、高度な金属でさえ
朽ち果てているはずだ

72
00:05:55,530 --> 00:05:59,030
 If they dug up canals, cleared forests and built cities, 
運河を掘り、森林を拓き
都市を築いたとしても

73
00:05:59,030 --> 00:06:02,250
their traces would be very hard to distinguish from nature.
その痕跡はもはや
自然物と見分けがつかない

74
00:06:02,250 --> 00:06:08,040
Maybe there once was an empire of cephalopods occupying impressive cities in swamps and lakes, 
沼や池で素晴らしい都市を築いた
頭足類の帝国があったかも

75
00:06:08,040 --> 00:06:10,520
made from wood and stone.  
建材は木と石だ

76
00:06:10,520 --> 00:06:17,370
Their engineers flooding land to build wet cities, their poets reciting poems in a language of colors. 
エンジニアは浸水により湿った都市を築き
詩人は色を言語として詩を詠んだ

77
00:06:17,370 --> 00:06:19,700
Maybe they never industrialized 
おそらく工業化には至らず

78
00:06:19,700 --> 00:06:25,280
– maybe their society was too stable or not inventive enough or they never got a chance. 
原因は社会の安定感か、不十分な発明性か
単に機会に恵まれなかったのかも

79
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:31,400
A single event like an asteroid, an epidemic or an ice age could just have deleted their civilization, 
そして小惑星や疫病、氷河期といった
単発の出来事でも文明は消滅し

80
00:06:31,400 --> 00:06:35,650
ground up their temples as their soft bodies rotted away. 
柔らかな身体は朽ち果て
寺院もすり潰されうる

81
00:06:35,650 --> 00:06:40,750
Sadly we don’t have the tiniest amount of evidence for any such civilization.
だが残念ながら、そのような文明について
かすかな証拠すらない

82
00:06:40,750 --> 00:06:46,540
After a few million years at best, their achievements would have dissolved into nothing.
せいぜい数百万年後には
彼らの実績は無に帰してしまうだろう

83
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:49,610
Industrial Indigenous Aliens
工業的な土着の知的生命体

84
00:06:49,610 --> 00:06:54,270
What about industrial civilizations, like humanity today?
現在の人類のような
工業文明はどうだろう

85
00:06:54,270 --> 00:07:01,220
Imagine humans died out suddenly, through a pandemic or cosmic rays or something like that.
パンデミックや宇宙線などで
人類が突如として滅亡した場合を想像しよう

86
00:07:01,220 --> 00:07:02,910
What would remain?
何が残るだろう

87
00:07:02,910 --> 00:07:07,980
Our impact on the planet is orders of magnitude greater than that of our ancestors.  
私たちが地球に与える影響は
祖先よりも桁外れに大きい

88
00:07:07,980 --> 00:07:11,340
The fossil record will show a great extinction of wildlife
化石記録から、野生動物の大絶滅と

89
00:07:11,340 --> 00:07:18,000
and an explosion of fossils from human associated animals, like rats, cows, pigs and chickens. 
ラット、牛、豚、鶏といった
人類に関わる動物化石の爆発的な増加がわかるだろう

90
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,270
Like the structures of our ancestors,
祖先の建造物と同様

91
00:07:20,270 --> 00:07:26,730
skyscrapers and streets and harddrives will basically crumble into nothingness in a few millennia.
高層ビルや道路、ハードディスクは
基本的に数千年で崩れ、無に帰すだろう

92
00:07:26,730 --> 00:07:29,320
But because there were so many humans everywhere,
だが人間はどこにでも多数いたので

93
00:07:29,320 --> 00:07:34,850
唐突な絶滅から数百万年は
人類の存在を示唆するものがあるはずだ

94
00:07:34,850 --> 00:07:41,980
The byproducts of our industrial lifestyle might actually give us away for some hundreds of millions of gas.
私たちの工業的なライフスタイルの副産物は
数億年にわたり痕跡を残すかもしれない

95
00:07:41,980 --> 00:07:44,900
We use massive amounts of artificial fertilizer
私たちが利用する大量の化学肥料は

96
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:49,500
which redirects earth’s flow of nitrogen that is being deposited in the soil. 
地球の窒素循環の流れを変え
土壌に蓄積させていく

97
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:55,970
Mining metals and rare Earth elements leaves long term scars and depletes natural resources. 
金属やレアアースの採掘は長期の傷跡を残し
天然資源を枯渇させる

98
00:07:55,970 --> 00:08:00,110
We saturate our oceans with plastics that find their way to the ocean floor  
海をプラスチックで満たし
それが海底に到達すると

99
00:08:00,110 --> 00:08:03,360
and may persist for hundreds of millions of years.
数億年にわたり残留しうる

100
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:05,930
There are radioactive elements and their decay, 
放射性元素とその崩壊について

101
00:08:05,930 --> 00:08:11,480
unnatural accumulations of elements that do not exist outside labs or weapons. 
研究所や兵器以外ではありえない
不自然な集積がある

102
00:08:11,480 --> 00:08:14,050
 And of course, in our short industrial history
そしてもちろん
短い産業史のなかで

103
00:08:14,050 --> 00:08:19,760
we have changed the proportion of CO2 in the air by burning massive amounts of fossil fuels,
私たちは大量の化石燃料を燃やして
大気中のCO2濃度を変え

104
00:08:19,760 --> 00:08:23,040
increasing the acidity of the oceans and so on.
海の酸性度を高めたりしてきた

105
00:08:23,040 --> 00:08:27,540
We may already have left a mark in the geological record.
すでに地質学的な記録に
痕跡を残しているのかもしれない

106
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:32,390
So far we have found no traces of an industrial alien civilization.  
今のところ、知的生命体による
産業文明の痕跡は見つかっていない

107
00:08:32,390 --> 00:08:35,700
No layers of weird chemicals or displaced elements. 
奇妙な化学物質の層や
元素が収集された層もない

108
00:08:35,700 --> 00:08:41,100
 No radioactive layer to indicate that once great nations waged nuclear war. 
大国による核戦争を示唆するような
放射性物質の層もない

109
00:08:41,100 --> 00:08:45,350
We do see mass extinctions and massive shifts in the fossil records 
化石記録から大量絶滅や
大規模移動が示唆されるが

110
00:08:45,350 --> 00:08:48,490
but no evidence that they did not occur naturally.
その自然発生を否定する材料はない

111
00:08:48,490 --> 00:08:52,370
And ironically we’ve hit upon an interesting problem here:
皮肉なことに
ここで興味深い問題に直面した

112
00:08:52,370 --> 00:08:56,800
If industrial societies stress the ecosystem enough to cause their own extinction, 
もし産業社会が、自滅を招くほど
生態系に負荷をかけるなら

113
00:08:56,800 --> 00:08:59,170
they won’t be around that long. 
長くは続かないだろうが

114
00:08:59,170 --> 00:09:04,780
But if they become sustainable their imprint on the geological record may be tiny. 
もし持続可能な社会になれば
地質学的記録への痕跡はごく小さいかも

115
00:09:04,780 --> 00:09:09,050
If past industrial civilizations were sustainable before they died out, 
過去の産業文明が
持続可能だったなら

116
00:09:09,050 --> 00:09:12,830
we may have little to no chance of ever knowing about them.
彼らを知るチャンスは
ほとんど無いかもしれない

117
00:09:12,830 --> 00:09:15,800
In any case, over hundreds of millions of years 
いずれにせよ、数億年を経て

118
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:21,730
these signatures may become very subtle and get overlooked or interpreted as natural. 
これらの痕跡はごく微妙なものとなり
見過ごされたり、自然の範囲内と解釈されうる

119
00:09:21,730 --> 00:09:26,690
Even if an industrialized alien society existed 200 million years ago
仮に知的生命体の社会が2億年前に工業化し

120
00:09:26,690 --> 00:09:32,020
and lasted for 100,000 years, 300 times longer than industrial humanity, 
人類の300倍にあたる
10万年を存続したとして

121
00:09:32,020 --> 00:09:35,920
it still might be easy to miss it in the geological record.
彼らの地質学的記録は
容易に見落されるかもしれない

122
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:39,610
In any case, all of this is speculation. 
いずれにせよ、全ては憶測だ

123
